Creating images with R

With a little bit of magick

Eli Chandler

2023-03-07

My meme

My meme is a take on the ‘distracted boyfriend’ format, where the boyfriend in the image, is distracted by another girl. The woman on the right, is probably the one he should be paying attention to, but he is looking at the one on the left. In this case, the joke is that programmers should probably be using stackoverflow when they get stuck, but sometimes if we are lazy we just get chatGPT to do what we want. 

library(magick)


top_text <- image_blank(500, 50, "black") %>% # Creates blank black rectangle we can add text onto
  image_annotate("Coders in 2023", gravity="center", color="white", font="impact", size=45) #Font size lower than size of image so it doesn't get cut off


meme_template <- image_read("https://media.wired.com/photos/59a459d1e5238d59ce11404f/master/w_2560%2Cc_limit/MemeLoveTriangle_297886754.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500) %>% # Scale set same as top_text so it can be stacked properly 
  image_annotate('Stack\nOverflow',
                 gravity="east",
                 size=20,
                 font="impact",
                 color="white",
                 strokecolor="black",
                 location="+60+0") %>%
  image_annotate('ChatGPT',
                 gravity='west',
                 size=20,
                 font="impact",
                 color="white",
                 strokecolor="black",
                 location="+100+0")

images = c(top_text, meme_template)

image_write(image_append(images, stack=TRUE), 'my_meme.png')

My animated gif

My animation is inspired by the old DVD player screensaver animations. I remember watching it until it would bounce in the corner, so I made a gif that is only corner bounces. I made it change color and have a fading effect to make it more visually interesting. 

library(magick)

dvd_logo <- image_read("https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/DVD_logo.svg/2560px-DVD_logo.svg.png") %>%
  image_resize("128x72!") %>% # ! forces scaling, because we need a 16:9 aspect ratio
  image_negate()

dvd_rainbow = c(
  image_colorize(dvd_logo, 100,"red"),
  image_colorize(dvd_logo, 100,"yellow"),
  image_colorize(dvd_logo, 100,"green"),
  image_colorize(dvd_logo, 100,"cyan"),
  image_colorize(dvd_logo, 100,"violet")
)

blank_frame <- image_blank(640, 360, color="black") # 16:9 aspect ratio


frame1 <- image_composite(blank_frame, dvd_rainbow[1], "over", offset="+0+0") # Increase by 128 x 72 each time
frame2 <- image_composite(blank_frame, dvd_rainbow[2], "over", offset="+128+72")
frame3 <- image_composite(blank_frame, dvd_rainbow[3], "over", offset="+256+144")
frame4 <- image_composite(blank_frame, dvd_rainbow[4], "over", offset="+384+216")
frame5 <- image_composite(blank_frame, dvd_rainbow[5], "over", offset="+512+288")



frames = c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4, frame5)
animation_sequence = c(frames, rev(frames[c(-1, -5)]), frames[1]) # We can re-use the middle section of the vector if we reverse it!
# I chose to add frame 1 onto the end again, because it made the image_morph look better!)
animation <- image_morph(animation_sequence) %>%
  image_animate(50)
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
